### Solution #1: `HashSet`

A good solution to the immediate problem of reading a file into an `ArrayList` with a uniqueness constraint is to simply keep a [`HashSet`](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/HashSet.html) of seen items. Before processing a line, we check that its key is not already in the set. If it isn&#39;t, we add the key to the set to mark it as finished, then add the line data to the result `ArrayList`. 

    import java.util.*;
    import java.io.*;
    
    public class Main {
        public static void main(String[] args) 
            throws FileNotFoundException, IOException {
            
            String file = &quot;prova.txt&quot;;
            ArrayList&lt;String[]&gt; data = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
            HashSet&lt;String&gt; seen = new HashSet&lt;&gt;();
    
            try (BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new FileReader(file))) {
                for (String line; (line = br.readLine()) != null;) {
                    String[] split = line.split(&quot;\\s+&quot;);
                    String key = split[0] + &quot; &quot; + split[1];
    
                    if (!seen.contains(key)) {
                        data.add(Arrays.copyOfRange(split, 2, split.length));
                        seen.add(key);
                    }
                }
            }
    
            for (String[] row : data) {
                System.out.println(Arrays.toString(row));
            }
        }
    }

